[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing native reflection issues**\n\nI'm trying to figure out why native fails due to missing reflection metadata for a method. So, I need to catch only Error, not Exception. The user mentioned not to skip tests, especially with dynamic class loading, where unsupported Error occurs. It seems like the tests should pass, but can I catch NoSuchMethodException instead? I need to consider if direct reflection in tests could generate required metadata, but is that allowed? I wonder if generated metadata should be included after the agent runs.\n\n**Exploring native class loading issues**\n\nI'm pondering why getDeclaredMethod on SecuritySupport12 in native might throw a NoSuchMethodException, suggesting it uses JDK class, not missing metadata. The issue seems tied to the JDK's internal classes, which lack the method. My custom classloader in Native Image can’t load new classes from URLs, and instead, it resolves to existing classes. Even though dynamic class loading isn't supported in the native runtime, it seems the URLClassLoader behaves differently. I wonder if I should catch NoSuchMethodException only during Native Image execution.\n\n**Examining dynamic class loading limitations**\n\nI’m considering how explicit guards ban early returns and whether I can treat NoSuchMethodException from dynamic class loading as unsupported. NativeImageSupport only catches Error, and the rule states that I should catch Error for dynamic loading issues and rethrow if unsupported. It doesn't mention checked exceptions, so maybe wrapping NoSuchMethodException into an Assertion isn't the best idea. I think it might be better not to include native dynamic class loading and use the public API instead. But if the artifact was loaded at build, how can I ensure coverage while forcing an UnsupportedFeatureError in native?\n\n**Exploring Java API Options**\n\nI’m considering whether I can use the compile-time JDK API instead of the artifact, and it looks like there's no coverage for that. Perhaps I could keep the testing Java only and avoid skipping native altogether. Yet, I’m also pondering the limitations with the public API and reflection. It seems that calling `DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance()` might engage the JDK’s SecuritySupport. I wonder if using `ServiceLoader` would be viable, but I'm hesitant about that too.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0266ed53936078e50169f540ce91f0819c9253e935addc8110\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9UDfKPjjeBHs-nLg7ZGxtAJCtd-9nfVJreGukrRCYlprEDjehBFs5fsrMZqARyu-nqG9PfBuNKXHZiqyGpdurbTHmhbpHiMbNxhMoVuJbyOk3U7QaPcDUvzWKoIbwu-UTuZkkEd9FVtlo73ezui5lgq9Xc6pLDJjESD6NMx7S9tyMvYpfZ1VXxD4lwcF6yIGJ5KbQ2G0FBhyo6TWP0lr9FQwxiJWFue3MGdheY_wbXnBEIzcTnvk7vhOh2WvbfD-V6Ih7wqsgNIGJfV21Qa747_shS8O0Wx6vb-b9UsUq1uHQWVWgUq0WRTZeaAF0bi_BcOdOOJxZhUTB3YgVMrNUKrKIFrkR4MCNFCKL1VAlPQCSycEc8ghmaZjM6Q9EexTRDpacOemiKk7nxnZHrNHLTXUXsQLYhvSnuih6ml1zShaWsHUF_tTgovBGnBsFMr4LwkOEmIbMOmGhBL5ug_6tTufpcRuVzpPCg6yTSjh4p_42N5l4oi7yd_LVR-oXR8wIWHbgjEGGgmldScHF3ZJ5hRZK8WmA43p-SZWJG8IwxZzCcrlQVbo6m0nuitNJwTyPxD6-loU1mptDO4irxuZJ02hhuO7484saEQUK16PSVRtAyMDIZJeUJWTCyWWAia36ouMm1W4PQ7Aut5u7zRH50suYIseUpHpvY8SJUsPx9QJTqs_zHPGPE5acIgnbMsDlqmPRYu2-bes3UNMQrQZmUOandlJC0J8-x5Gnuf3R2EZNmCpix4y8bnNO7KEnnUIvFrwxnMP9cmGins0UVS6_z_sQMFixA8wUe_nqTe8k3WqL26AnoTkGVQd5DRVZOQnpMPsRk3J9YkZ6W8ww6Bp9Y2Ik149xt6LVYGzThOks56DVVxeA4nX14d7Mh163mGLabVC5AqaLMm59fPEhj-SlJ3rLbgPmkYlsB92Gk24Wc7WEJ2LbOyrrt0M9QeRCYuZ56mGX6cOaiJ-slCpg7giOp8lBUbbk_7MHf6b4T9xhSJX-VTCEN0zaZm09AMIe2d7GbrWia-xBFBMfK_BoTerWmW_h7opF4cw98zaX6Fh0t9qmdHLKRXjYMkZ821RoU-5gNTm9kWDn2M16NS-eug2SS85T3ciUcTYOiD70P0Kg0a2kgeQUIjKlxfYD2tF14Xas8iAucFP0RnV2grHWOkKEsjKn2y2i0w5DgjO0TdynAmLNuy4aGiPut5BXsCglOZr51LQ6_wRmypa2iMFAi6BSWRBX145oyHPtAw5oNiep98lpgYlNQTnGp_N1G5XMAHbH8voC7kCn2mReG1KhdHC-SOuVJuqgeVLg2rLlIct2wSkwi3vDsbDKxy8yD5FkqJOdwD-TkKNO7VvJ6Y_W6grzwW0uTmaDF82M3TZAJzgkCKEpj-UjPYIYn1x7BIndHj